<li id="cite_note-Seema-240"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Seema_240-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFSohi2014" class="citation book cs1">Sohi, Seema (2014). <i>Echoes of Mutiny: Race, Surveillance, and Indian Anticolonialism in North America</i>. Oxford University Press. p.&#160;8. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-937625-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-937625-4"><bdi>978-0-19-937625-4</bdi></a>. <q>Indians in North America, nearly 90 percent of whom where Sikhs from the state of Punjab, were also racialized through colonial gendered discourses. During the early decades of the twentieth century, US Immigration, Justice, and State Department officials cast Indian anti-colonialists as a "Hindu" menace</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Echoes+of+Mutiny%3A+Race%2C+Surveillance%2C+and+Indian+Anticolonialism+in+North+America&amp;rft.pages=8&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-937625-4&amp;rft.aulast=Sohi&amp;rft.aufirst=Seema&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARacism+in+the+United+States" class="Z3988"></span></span>
